But in any exchange, a central authority controls and treats changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both deposits of accounting books, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes of bitcoins are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file sliced, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "throat" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular fingerprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different prints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the 100th century, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in the power of calculation.
The life of the network already has its heights.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in storage.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using Bitcoin network.
