A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever about the constitutional declaration, which grants it provisional full powers, he decided to play the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on his final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given that Assembly two more months to finish his work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used an interim text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial misappropriation.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delusion" and continues "treasoning his word" and "footing the law."
By their supporters, it is ensured that this is a step to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organized in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote on my text or I maintain the full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in large majority, voted the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not go to the summons.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt that they could not put their views into practice.
Human rights representatives, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added to the morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As I had hoped, the articles voted were unanimously.
The commentators, on the other hand, are pleased that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, subject to all looks, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the norms", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals view it as hypocrisy and believe it is nothing more than an art of advertising.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which gives the Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm his compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next director of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
Most jurists who have worked in that text are not ugly but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But recognize that there may be some ambiguity about article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, Ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule over all of this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those who were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
The prosecution of civilians in military courts will also not be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be libertic.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could lead to serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, points out Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive step was the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was scheduled to leave last night on television, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state expressed themselves on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await the Holy Land, the shadow of the world and a sea of salmon
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and a pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pillar" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of the miracles of Jesus: the conversion of water into wine in the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the nets filled.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the largest number of holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (latinian "Dolorous Way").
It begins in the Fortaleza de Antonio, the Pretorio, where the trial took place, and continues along the streets of the Old City, it goes to the Holy Sepulchre in Mount Gólgota, the place of crucifixion, the Stone of the Unction and the place of burial of Jesus.
In this same place there is also the symbolic Christian Ombudsman of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 AD.
As it is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their desires, which will then come true.
Perform a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great commanded to build in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located in the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And get there by your own means, only those who engage in climbing can.
Others can reach this historic summit in the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a great influx of tourists.
Up to there, from the foot of the hill are offered bus services.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly inhabited on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are about 300 museums.
On a single trip you will not be able to visit all of them.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
In it are preserved the ancient Manuscripts of the Dead Sea or Rollos de Qumran, discovered in the caves of the desert of Judaea, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his painting exhibition he has paintings of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bath-museum, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth passing through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides and no souvenir shops there.
The entrance is free, and categorically no donations are accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section is the Children ' s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars shine.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives sound.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphins and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop from 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustains even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People arrive here to pass treatment courses with salt water, brine and curative bars and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their nerve fractures in order.
Touching the Mysteries of Old Age
It preserves the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
She passed through the famous maritime route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this was where Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the Zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your symbol "meism", the fortune will be for you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph themselves.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusades.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The theater, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists Remember
If you travel to Israel, do not worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to take it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently $1-3.8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a quick tram and in Haifa is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the High City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling in any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated.
From Friday night until Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning begins a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb meat, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, the falafel, which are soft chick balls, fruits and vegetables.
No street dogs are seen on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats who "walk to their taste" imposingly.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of cars parked.
Runners love the crowded places and do not reject the greedy ones.
Car rental, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, it leaves for $15 a day.
And renting a bike will leave you for 15 shekels the day.
The entrances to the museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012 over three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who arrived to travel and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, a quantity exceeding 51 per cent at the same rate as in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on 9 February 2011.
