Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are the immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without the understanding of the language, says Sebelev, the immigrant future will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, on the pretext of helping, throw a "paid journey" into a creepy and close coat, where he and dozens of others like him will be consumed for months without food or documents, working from 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they promise one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," confirms the Head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be angry, boss!
However, in the meantime many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to work in Russia recognize that they do not only know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write in their own language with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbek, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to give to feed the children, not to talk anymore about dressing them, shoes them, and buying them what they need for school.
As they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work on the first chance.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize it.
