The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can control only federal money, which we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by regions and municipalities, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors there in Germany.
As far as local legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to draw up a comparison without specific data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be specified exactly where it is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kind of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it didn't, it wouldn't be good for you to work with our office, would it?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is it in any way apparent its impact?
Given that the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been demonstrated in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post controls, a certain delay is necessary.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", whereby we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial or, rather, is it a misunderstanding for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is probably a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations "harden" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
With the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in the area of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision making.
A system of this kind will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then even the prime minister of the government can not prevent the performance of the Office which has the obligation to carry out such controls and require obligations.
He can say, "We change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we'll do as if nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, legislation is fairly strict as to how it should be done formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
On the other hand, it is tragic to exclude the candidate with the best offer not to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. That is, in my opinion, what we lack.
