Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of the ESA of the former bloc of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's way to the cosmos began a long time ago.
The Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before the Second World War, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie award and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world, and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
Already in 1925, in Poland, a drain was built that would be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the project highlights are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the drain or for its braking.
Information on this area is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
Based on the stored material, it is clear that the investigation came to the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna and rakietomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile engineering projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautica (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of Problemy magazine, the first reference is made to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would devote itself to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautica Society (PTA) had aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautica (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year Kazimierz Zarankiewicz, PTA first president (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He took this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the rocket probe MRI (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and launched for the first time on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 metres, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was built and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rocket air tests were started in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1,4 meters high and weighed about 11,5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a height of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the height wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a rocket of two stages, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum height in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first air tests of which began in October 1970.
The meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined in research on cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
