Last week, the constitutional court suspended the law on social work.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is at the beginning of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of major differences in labour costs (wages) is economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, tries to shorten distance and for this purpose "causes a decline" in the price of the competitor with the aim of making itself with most of the market and thus increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, to move production abroad, to buy there cheaper or to disappear. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, it is not responsible for the unemployment generated by this phenomenon, it necessarily increases the social spending of the state.
All of this leads to the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and to compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in their efforts to obtain benefits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create situations, in certain economies, in which the Governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thereby attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments place private capital at the disposal of their own people without regard for social decline.
This is particularly evident in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictatorship of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, by the restricted right of employees with regard to labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, food delivery points have existed in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people who receive this kind of help is already up to the million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a quite frequent case: people employed with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest in order to get to the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public in connection with the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The measures to save virtually all the states in the south of the EU are undoubtedly leading to the same situation. People, pressured by an abyss of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to maleviate with a pessim wage within society, in the hope that one day they will reach the private capital country.
