The conclusion, in the same way as in antiquity, is that today's society is based on dismissive preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not, in essence, able to understand and claim the benefits of the entire society.
The result is the same as that of then, a decadence of the unprecedented elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With regard to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, such as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
