In the Friday view, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers completed after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was held in maximum prison from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning and noted his answers.
When Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the cellers as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about certain issues and that the officers who visited him had spoken of those problems and indicated that they would be concerned, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'without incident' (after having talked about problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I would not have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Army Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council to examine the intentions of suicide that he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was present.
