He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Arafjon Camp, that cage," Manning said on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning said that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a claws, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since he was forbidden to sleep or even fall during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from the outside pointing to his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the janitors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on treatment received by Manning.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in the Thursday declaration that, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to remain naked in front of the cinders and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the order given by the cellor that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that they had forced him to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his heels to self-injurious but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed their underwear, shawls, and glasses from their cells.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he had experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted on the war council, which is scheduled to start early next year.
The defence stated that it intends to have Manning convicted of minor crimes and to defend other charges considered to be too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detained person who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally triggering the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from national defence and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
