On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about the boredom that dates back to the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and raising the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desiring, but not being able to, participate in an activity that fills you."
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he states, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boring can sound terribly similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider it their problem.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of the magazine Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants heard a tape of a person who read the article of a magazine.
Some groups heard in the room a full-volume television program that did not keep any relationship, others heard it with the low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of care can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
