Our objective should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our way of seeing, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate it to something worth the trouble," he says.
It points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
